<DOC><DOCNO> AP890303-0125 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 1943EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-03 0433</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0442</SECOND><HEAD>Snow Storm Moves Into Nation's Midsection</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A winter storm that had blitzed the Northwest with up to 18inches of snow moved across the Rockies and toward the nation'smidsection Friday, dumping heavy snow on Colorado and Minnesota.   Snowfall totals in Colorado ranged up to 16 inches at SteamboatLake, and in the upper Mississippi Valley, up to 9 inches of snowblanketed southwestern Minnesota.   Snow advisories were in effect for the mountains of Iowa, andwinter storm warnings issued for the southern and central mountainsof Colorado, the southern mountains of Wyoming, northern Iowa, andmuch of Nebraska, Wisconsin and Michigan.   Temperatures were in the single digits or below zero from thenorthern half of the high Plains to upper Michigan and northernMinnesota at midday. Strong and gusty winds in the central highPlains were expected to cause near-blizzard conditions Friday nightand Saturday and produce wind chill readings to 40 degrees belowzero.   Heavier snowfall totals for the six-hour period ending at 1 p.m.EST included 5 inches at Milwaukee, 4 inches at Green Bay and 3inches at Madison, Wis.   Sleet and freezing rain fell from eastern Nebraska tosouthwestern Michigan, changing to rain from northeast Oklahoma tocentral Illinois. Rain also fell over much of the Southern Atlanticstates.   Arctic air settled into the northwestern United States in thewake of the snowstorm. Temperatures dipped well below freezingacross the Pacific Northwest. Astoria, Klamath Falls and Portland,Ore., had record low temperatures for the date, with readings of 25,10 and 19 degrees, respectively.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 9 belowzero at Cutbank, Mont., to 84 degrees at Miami and St. Petersburg,Fla. The morning low for the nation was minus 26 at Warroad, Minn.   Saturday's forecast called for snow from the southern and centralRockies to the upper Great Lakes, turning to rain farther south andeast. Scattered thunderstorms were expected from the lowerMississippi Valley to the southern Appalachians. Fair to partlysunny skies should prevail elsewhere.   Highs should be below freezing from the northern and central highPlains and northwest Texas, most of Michigan and northern Maine,dipping into the teens from Nebraska and the Dakotas to Minnesota.Highs above 50 were forecast from western Oregon through Californiaand western Nevada to southern Arizona and southwestern New Mexico,the Rio Grande Valley the Ohio and Tennessee valleys and the centralGulf Coast states, warming into the 70s and 80s in southernCalifornia, southwestern Arizona, south-central Texas, Florida,Georgia and South Carolina.</TEXT></DOC>